Driving in high heels is dangerous!
Accidents involving young people stepping on the wrong pedal occur frequently (Auto Messe Web) --Yahoo! News
Violations that violate the Road Traffic Act
There have been more and more reports of accidents caused by mishandling of pedals, but it would be a big mistake to think that this is a problem only for elderly drivers.
According to the 2015 National Police Agency data, the largest number of accidents involving pedal misstepping by age group was 1,080 for those aged 24 or younger, exceeding the 1,032 accidents for those aged 75 and over.
Missteps are not common among the elderly, and it is important to call attention to young people as well.
Do you want to dress up on your feet?
Do you take safety?
The data does not describe the gender ratio or causes, but unlike the elderly, who are often thought to be due to physical deterioration such as driving skills and reflexes, young people may make inadvertent mistakes due to distractions such as music or conversation, or may make mistakes due to clothing.
Women, in particular, choose a variety of shoes depending on what they are wearing that day, such as high heels, pumps, sandals, and mules, and some people drive as they are.
Some people find it troublesome to change their shoes even though they know they are not suitable for driving, but there are many people who drive without any ill will, not thinking about the possibility of danger at all.
However, driving in high heels or sandals is a violation of the Road Traffic Act.
The first is Article 70, which stipulates that "the driver must operate the steering wheel, brakes, and other operations reliably" and "the driver must not drive in a way that causes an accident and harms others."
The other is Article 71 "Violation of the Public Safety Commission's Compliance Matters," which stipulates that the driver must comply with the matters stipulated by the prefectural public safety commission, for example, Article 12 of the Miyazaki Prefecture Road Traffic Law Enforcement Detailed Regulations states, "Wearing bald, slippers, hooks, high heels, or other footwear that may interfere with driving operations, or wearing footwear in a way that interferes with driving operations, and using a vehicle (excluding light vehicles). Don't drive. There is a sentence that says.
Each prefecture has the same intent to consider driving in "footwear that may interfere with driving operations" as a violation, even if it is not specified as high heels.
So why is it dangerous to drive in high heels?
This is obvious when you consider the basics of safe pedaling.
In order to operate the pedal safely and reliably, first fix the heel of the foot on the floor, place the foot so that it is perpendicular to the brake pedal, and tilt the toe to the right using that as a fulcrum when stepping on the accelerator pedal.
At this time, regardless of the behavior of the car, it is important to keep the heel firmly fixed so that it does not shake.
However, with high heels, the area where the heel touches the floor is small, and it always wobbles, and because the entire foot is angled at the height of the heel, the area of the foot that touches the pedal is also small, making it difficult to step firmly and make fine adjustments.
This is considered to lead to danger.
In addition, most cars have a floor carpet, but the heel of the high heel is easily caught in this material, and when braking suddenly, the heel may get caught and the pedal may not be able to be pressed, or the high heel may come off when the heel is caught and may be caught in the back of the pedal and cannot be stepped on.
In addition, there have been cases where the heel caught on the back of the pedal when returning after pressing the pedal, and the accelerator pedal could not return.
