WASHINGTON -- The U.S. State Department announced on Monday that it will reduce the maximum number of refugees accepted from around the world to 18,000 in fiscal year 2020 (Oct. 19 ~ Sep. 20).
This is the third consecutive year that the number of refugees has been the lowest since the Refugee Act was enacted in 1980.
The Trump administration is aiming to appeal to conservatives with its strict immigration and refugee policies in anticipation of next year's presidential election.
As people continue to flee their countries in many places, it is inevitable that there will be criticism from human rights groups and others.
The former Obama administration set the upper limit at 110,000 for FY17, but the Trump administration, which was inaugurated in January 2017, overturned this and reduced it to 50,000.
The number has been decreasing year by year, from 45,000 in FY18 to 30,000 in FY19.
