One year after the <Eastern Iburi Earthquake> securing water even in the event of a power outage Proceed with the installation of "sprinkler taps" directly connected to water pipes Hakodate's condominium: Hokkaido Shimbun Doshin electronic version
In response to the blackout caused by the Eastern Iburi Earthquake in September last year, countermeasures are underway at condominiums in Hakodate City, where the water outage occurred.
According to the Water Supply and Sewerage Department of the Municipal Enterprise Bureau, in the year after the earthquake, seven condominium buildings installed "sprinkler taps" that can dispense water even if the power goes out.
There are about 400 condominiums and private apartment buildings with four floors or more in the city that supply water through a "water tank" system, which may cut off water in the event of a power outage, and the ministry is calling for consideration of countermeasures.
There are two main types of water supply methods for houses: the "receiving tank type" in which water is stored in a receiving tank located underground or on the rooftop, and the "direct connection type" in which water is supplied directly to each house from the city's water distribution pipes.
In the receiving tank type, even if the water pipe is not damaged, if the electric pump that pumps water from the receiving tank to each house stops working due to a power outage, etc., water cannot be supplied and each house will be cut off.
