"Beauty and ugliness" are one and the same?
What is the image of "snake" that overlaps the beautiful girls of Kazuo Yuzu's work (Magmix) --Yahoo! News
What do mysterious beauty and shadowy expressions have in common?
In August 2019, the "Kazuo Kazuo Bishoujo Collection" (Genkosha) was released, focusing on beautiful girls drawn by Kazuo Yuzu, who has released numerous works to the world since the 1950s and is known as a leading expert in "horror manga".
When I pick it up and look at it, I am reminded of the correlation between "beauty" and "fear" in Kazuo Yuzu's work.
[Image] Is it attractive because there is a "shadow"?
Beautiful girls of Kazuo Yuzu's work (5 photos)
In the prologue of the "Bishoujo Collection", there is a sentence that says, "The beauty of these women, which is the opposite of the horror, ugliness, shocking scenes and developments of the story, stands out", but the beautiful face is distorted and changed to an expression of resentment with a grudge ... ... It may be because of this contrast that "fear" stands out more.
The keyword "snake" is often used in Kazuo Yuzu's works, and snakes are perceived in various ways, from being perceived as "creepy creatures" by some people to being "beautiful" depending on the viewer.
There are people in the world who like reptiles, and there are people who just don't like it.
In this way, depending on the sensibility of the viewer, a creature in which "beauty" and "ugliness" are inextricably linked may be a "snake".
In addition, this creature has been revered as a creature with high spiritual power since ancient times, and it is said that the house where the "white snake" settled is auspicious.
Two of his works based on the snake are "Snake Girl" and "Mottled Girl" from the 1965 "I'm Afraid of Mommy!" series.
It is generally the market that the "snake woman" is a beautiful woman with a shadow.
To put it in a crazy way, I would say that I am a "cool buty" type ... ... I feel that this is the common point of the beautiful girls who appear in Yuzu's works.
Among them, "Orochi", the main character of "Orochi", which was serialized in "Weekly Shonen Sunday" from 1969, is a beautiful girl character that can be said to be a representative of Yuzu's works, but the part that goes into a deep sleep every hundred years in order to maintain eternal life and eternal youth, and the part that has mysterious powers, is somewhat reminiscent of "snake".
