How to prevent dementia and keep it to the level of "forgetfulness"?
Interview and text: Yo Watanabe
Major pharmaceutical companies and university hospitals have tried to research and develop drugs for dementia and have been frustrated.
However, the relationship between dementia and lifestyle habits is being elucidated, and it seems that it has become clear that it may be possible to keep it to the extent of extremely mild illness and forgetfulness.
We interviewed Professor Shunsuke Otsuki of the Stroke Center, University Hospital.
Dementia doesn't go away
― ― There is a long-awaited anticipation of dementia prevention or treatment, but what is the current situation?
Otsuki: From mild to severe, everyone can develop dementia as they age.
However, it is believed that it will still take more than 20 years for a new dementia drug to be developed.
Donepezil, a drug commonly used in Japan, is already not covered by insurance in some overseas countries, and a remarkable cure effect cannot be expected.
On the other hand, while deaths due to infectious diseases and accidents are decreasing, and cancer deaths are also decreasing due to remarkable advances in treatments such as anticancer drugs, people are now living longer.
Therefore, it is also true that the number of people with dementia is increasing.
It is not something that can be solved by the person or his or her family alone, but it is necessary for society as a whole to create an environment where people can live in the community with peace of mind.
How to keep it to the level of "forgetfulness"
― ― Are there people who are more likely or less likely to develop dementia?
Otsuki Even if dementia is unavoidable, there is a possibility that the symptoms can be suppressed as much as possible and kept to the level of "forgetfulness".
Dementia is considered to be one of the lifestyle-related diseases, and people who are susceptible to dementia tend to have it.
First of all, people with metabolic syndrome are more likely to develop dementia.
Dementia is regarded as a lifestyle-related disease.
It is a combination of obesity, high blood pressure, diabetes and high cholesterolemia.
The presence or absence of economic power also plays a role.
For example, in the United States, there are areas where food tickets are distributed to the poor, but the food you get with food tickets is non-perishable frozen hamburgers, pizza, and chicken.
It can be used by people who live in an environment where they cannot use gas or electricity and cannot cook in the first place.
As a result, you will end up with a diet low in vegetables and proteins, and your life will be biased toward fats and sugars.
Eventually, they become poor but obese, and the only thing they can do is watch TV in a daze, and they become physically disabled.
A similar situation could occur in Japan.
In addition, people who do not think or work tend to be more prone to dementia.
In other words, in order to prevent dementia, it is necessary to read books on a daily basis and think about things without metabolic syndrome.
