This program is a "health program for young people" in which Koyama, who has reached the age of 35 and has begun to worry about his own health, learns what he wants to know about his health.
The program features specialists from a variety of fields to answer questions from Koyama and his guests.
This year's theme is "Vitamins".
Guests Naoko Nozawa and Diana Extravaganza will be invited to learn about the different types of vitamins and how they work.
In addition, Koyama, who is careful about his health on a daily basis, has a plan to disclose the contents of his daily diet in order to confirm whether he is getting enough vitamins.
After finishing this recording, Koyama commented, "I think there are many people who seem to know how vitamins are related to their health, but they don't understand it, and I hope that this program will clear up the misconceptions they have about vitamins that it is not good to take only certain vitamins!"
Helped by Mr. Onsarigo Nagai, who served as a pacemaker in elementary school track and field, and three people broke the record of the competition|Yamagata Shimbun
Children running in the women's 800 meters.
On the left is pacemaker Joseph Onsarigo = Nagai City, Koyo Seiki Athlete Field Nagai
The Nagai City Elementary School Friendly Track and Field Tournament was held on the 26th at Koyo Seiki Athlete Field Nagai (Municipal Athletics Stadium) in the same city, and in some races, long-distance runner Joseph Onsarigo (27) = from Kenya = who belongs to Nasu Construction (the same city) served as a pacemaker.
With a light run, he "set the stage" for the three new records of the competition.
Onsaligo led the pupils in four races, the men's 1,000 meters and the women's 800 meters.
In the men's race, Tomoya Koseki (6th grade, Hirano Elementary School) took first place with a time of 3:04.38, and in the women's race, Ransei Shigama (6th grade, Isazawa Elementary School) set a time of 2:34.17 and Rin Asano (6th grade, Nagai Elementary School) finished second with a time of 2:35.73.
Mr. Koseki said, "It was hard to keep up with the fast Onsarigo, but I was able to endure it," and Mr. Shigama said, "Onsarigo said, 'Pick up the pace.'"
Onsaligo was delighted, saying, "The kids ran well, and I did a perfect job."
The tournament was organized by the Nagai City Elementary School Sports Promotion Association and other organizations to deepen friendship among sixth-grade elementary school students in the city, and was held for the 39th time.
