Cutting-edge art that invites you to another world Okayama Art Exchange opens in the city center: Sanyo Shimbun Digital |
People who visit the classroom that became the stage of the video work that depicts the future 3,000 years later = Former Uchiyamashita Elementary School
The international art exhibition "Okayama Art Exchange 2019" (organized by the executive committee of the city, prefecture, etc.), which is held every three years in the center of Okayama City, opened on the 27th.
In keeping with the enigmatic title "IF THE SNAKE," art fans from Japan and abroad enjoy cutting-edge art created by 18 artists from 9 countries.
This year's event, the second in a row for 16 years, has welcomed French artist Pierre Huyghe as artistic director and developed works that make use of the climate and local resources of Okayama.
Approximately 40 works of art and three-dimensional works will be exhibited at 13 locations, including the former Uchiyamashita Elementary School (Marunouchi, Kita-ku, Okayama City) and the Tenjinyama Cultural Plaza (Tenjin-cho).
Prior to the opening of the event, an opening ceremony was held at the same small school, attended by about 100 people.
Executive Committee Chairman, Mayor Masao Omori, and Executive Producer Yasuharu Ishikawa cut the ribbon, saying, "We have a collection of works that stimulate intellectual sensibilities and stimulate imagination and creativity, and we hope that this exhibition will attract attention from around the world."
Families and field trips were able to stare at the snake-shaped robots that wriggle in response to ambient sounds in the schoolyard, and tour the school building, which has been transformed into the stage for a film depicting the world 3,000 years in the future.
I was enjoying art that took me to another world.
A 15-year-old first-year high school student in Tokyo, who is traveling with his father, said, "It's interesting to see a work that makes use of the atmosphere of the old school building, and it makes me imagine the time that passed in this place."
Closed on Mondays (or the following day if it is a national holiday) until November 24.
Hong Kong, Umbrella Movement Rally for 5 Years, Tens of Thousands Aiming for Universal Suffrage|Shizuoka Shimbun ATS
People gathered at the rally venue to mark the 5th anniversary of the outbreak of the "Umbrella Movement" = 28th, Hong Kong (Kyodo)
HONG KONG (Kyodo) -- Tens of thousands of people gathered in a park near the Hong Kong government headquarters in Admiralty on March 28, five years after the Umbrella Movement, a large-scale demonstration calling for democracy in the election of Hong Kong's chief executive, which was the largest base of protesters.
Around the venue, some young people occupied the main road and threw Molotov cocktails at the government building.
As the protests sparked by the proposed amendment to the Fugitive Offenders Ordinance continued, the participants renewed their determination to fight for the realization of "true universal suffrage," which was unattainable at the time.
The protests, which began in earnest in June, lasted for 112 days, surpassing the 79 days of the Umbrella Movement, and the protesters' demands expanded to include the "five major demands," including electoral reform.
Ibaraki Kokutai opens on 28th|Sports|Saga Shimbun News|Saga Shimbun LiVE
The opening ceremony of the 74th National Sports Festival "Iki Iki Ibaraki Yume Kokutai 2019" will be held on October 28 at the Kasamatsu Sports Park Athletics Stadium in Hitachinaka City, Ibaraki Prefecture, and the 11-day competition will start until October 8.
Approximately 400 athletes, coaches, and other athletes and coaches will participate in 33 sports, excluding those held before the Games, and will take on the best teams from all over the country with the pride of their hometown.
Until two years ago, the prefectural team had been sluggish at 43rd place for three consecutive years, but last year it rose to 33rd place.
The team is also strengthening its skills for the national sports tournament to be held in the prefecture in 2023, and this year it has set a goal of finishing in the low 20s.
In the pre-exhibition competition held on the 16th, the rhythmic gymnastics boys' and girls' Saga Girls' High School and the adult girls and boys' and girls' gymnastics both finished in sixth place, gaining momentum.
I want to go with the flow of each sport and aim to advance to the top.
At the opening ceremony, a total of 83 players, coaches, and head office officials from the prefecture marched in the 40th place, with Kugo Ishikawa (Saga Koko) of the boys' rugby team serving as the flag bearer.
On the first day, there will be three sports: wrestling, table tennis, and karate.
